During a recent discussion I've had with {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://eur02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fjerkerdelsing&data=04%7C01%7C%7C6d7a2a1f4f47460fdba008d8e89006e3%7C5453408ba6cd4c1e8b1018b500fb544e%7C1%7C0%7C637515052576169117%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=WEoSUGexDkZFftw%2BIO1vrvi%2FSRLS%2Bn9rdPvMO%2BtomAw%3D&reserved=0"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 @jerkerdelsing}} about databases, it seems as if the idea is that all Arrowhead systems should use embedded databases, or at least start up and manage their own database processes. Ideally, the user of an Arrowhead system should have to do no database configuration or setup at all.\
While leaving it open for database clustering is standard practice in the context of the Internet, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://eur02.safelinks.protection.outlook.com/?url=https%3A%2F%2Fgithub.com%2Fjerkerdelsing&data=04%7C01%7C%7C6d7a2a1f4f47460fdba008d8e89006e3%7C5453408ba6cd4c1e8b1018b500fb544e%7C1%7C0%7C637515052576169117%7CUnknown%7CTWFpbGZsb3d8eyJWIjoiMC4wLjAwMDAiLCJQIjoiV2luMzIiLCJBTiI6Ik1haWwiLCJXVCI6Mn0%3D%7C1000&sdata=WEoSUGexDkZFftw%2BIO1vrvi%2FSRLS%2Bn9rdPvMO%2BtomAw%3D&reserved=0"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \ul \ulc4 \strokec4 @jerkerdelsing}} claims that it will rarely be directly relevant in the context of Arrowhead. In situation where would be relevant, my impression is that it should be facilitated by the way in which the Arrowhead systems themselves are connected, and not how their databases are.\
